==Treatment==
The standard approach to treatment is the same as with other phobias - cognitive-behavioral therapy, desensitization, and possibly medications  to help with the anxiety and discomfort.&nbsp; In recent years, the technique known as ''applied tension'', applying tension to the muscles in an effort to increase blood pressure, has increasingly gained favor as an often effective treatment for blood phobia associated with drops in blood pressure and fainting.<ref name="ost">{{Citation | last = Ost | first = L.G. | coauthors = ''et al.'' | title = Applied tension, exposure in vivo, and tension-only in the treatment of blood phobia | journal = Behaviour Research and Therapy | volume = 29 | issue = 6 | year = 1991 | pages = 561–574 | pmid = 1684704 | doi = 10.1016/0005-7967(91)90006-O | postscript = . }}</ref><ref name="ditto">{{Citation | last = Ditto | first = B. | coauthors = ''et al.'' | title = Physiological correlates of applied tension may contribute to reduced fainting during medical procedures | journal = [[Annals of Behavioral Medicine]] | volume = 37 | issue = 3 | year = 2009 | pages = 306–314 | pmid = 19730965 | doi = 10.1007/s12160-009-9114-7 | postscript = . }} </ref><ref name="Ayala">{{Citation | last = Ayala | first = E.S. | coauthors = ''et al.'' | title = Treatments for blood-injury-injection phobia: a critical review of current evidence | journal = Journal of Psychiatric Research | volume = 43 | issue = 15 | year = 2009 | pages = 1235–1242 REVIEW | pmid = 19464700 | doi = 10.1016/j.jpsychires.2009.04.008 | postscript = . }}</ref>
